taskGuess: shapes slide from one side to the other disappearing behind a curtain. when they come out the other side my job is to tell you if they changed or not by using the q key. this means they stayed the same, or the P key, which means they are different than before. THEN I have to tell you how certain I am
purposeGuess: My guess is that the square changing into a triangle was sort of the control, right? I mean anyone with a pulse will tell you that a square and a triangle are different...but the question is, can humans really differentiate  shapes once it starts to get significantly MORE complicated...and at what point do they start to just fail miserably??? I noticed there were a couple of shapes that at least to ME, seemed "not so hard" and yet other ones, I realized that were odd, complex and irregular _- it occurred to me that if the shape was SIMILAR but the proportions were a bit off here or there, there is NO WAY I would actually be able to tell simply because I have no real reference point for it in the real world the way I do for a circle, square, triangle, etc. When you did OBVIOUS things like ADD a sharp tringle/tail/turn or something to a shape that was not there before, I could obviously tell, but if you simply took a complex shape and made one part thicker and the other thinner, there is no way my brain would be able to accurrately differentiate that.
commentText: yeah, but I feel a little like Im not so clever, now, AND I think I have a bit of a headache?! have a great day, and good luck with your study. Go improve science!
